To proxy requests in an ASP.NET Core API, you can use the `HttpClient` class to make requests to the target endpoint and return the response to the client. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class ProxyController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public ProxyController(IHttpClientFactory httpClientFactory)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClientFactory.CreateClient();
    }

    [HttpGet("{endpoint}")]
    public async Task<IActionResult> Get([FromRoute] string endpoint)
    {
        var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Get, $"https://{endpoint}");
        var response = await _httpClient.SendAsync(request);

        if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            return new ContentResult
            {
                ContentType = "text/html",
                Content = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(),
                StatusCode = (int)response.StatusCode
            };
        }
        else
        {
            return StatusCode((int)response.StatusCode);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `ProxyController` has a single action method `Get` that takes an `endpoint` parameter. This parameter is used to construct the URL of the target endpoint.

